  - [ ] SDK API docs on https://docs.microsoft.com

**Describe the bug**
In the context of a session enabled subscription where the sessionRoundRobing is used to automatically lock on the next available session.

If the ``processMessage`` handler throw an error, ``processMessage`` is then **immediately** called again to retry the message.

In this situation, ``processError`` handler is in starvation, it almost never get a chance to handle the error for the current message. On my specific machine, the message was tried 4 times before the ``processError`` handler had a chance to be called once.

I also observed that ``processMessage`` is called more often than the configured **Max delivery count** on the subscription, leading me to believe that perhaps even the ``deliveryCount`` on the message is affected. With my test it seems that when ``processError`` is finally called, it stop the already running ``processMessage`` and this is when I can observe a disparity between ``msg.deliveryCount`` and the number of times that ``processMessage`` is called.

This isn't surprising but the issue is that we could be handling the first error encountered on the very first attempt at processing the message but it's interrupting the fourth attempt at processing the message. It seems that the two handlers are decoupled which could lead to issues if both ``processMessage`` and ``processError`` attempts to modify the same ressource, like a database entry, as part of their process.

Additionally, despite being in ``peekLock`` mode with ``autoCompleteMessages`` set to true, a ``processMessage`` handler that execute too quickly without any error will never complete the message. ``processMessage`` will continue to be called multiple time for the same message and the ``msg.deliveryCount`` stay at 0.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Slightly modify the [sessionRoundRobin.ts](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-js/blob/main/sdk/servicebus/service-bus/samples/v7/typescript/src/advanced/sessionRoundRobin.ts) sample to use topic - subscription instead of a queue.
2. Further modify the sample:
     1. Remove the ``refreshTimer`` and the explicit configuration to the ``maxAutoLockRenewalDurationInMs`` (the subscription set the message lock duration to 1 minute).
     2. In the ``processMessage`` function throw an error.
     3. Although unnecessary because this is the default value, set ``maxConcurrentCalls: 1``.
     4. Use ``await delay()`` to mimic processing time in both ``processMessage`` and ``processError`` handlers.
     5. Set ``maxSessionsToProcessSimultaneously`` to 1 to only allow one unique session at a time.

**Expected behavior**

1. I expected ``maxConcurrentCalls: 1`` to prevent a concurrent call between the ``processMessage`` handler and the ``processError`` handler. Because the type of the object passed to ``subscribe`` is called ``MessageHandlers`` and the documentation says ``The maximum number of concurrent calls that the library can make to the user's message handler`` it lead me to believe that the setting wouldn't affect the handlers individually but as a set.
2. I expect that for every error thrown by the ``processMessage``, the ``processError`` handler is executed. On my machine the message was attempted 10 times, 10 errors was thrown but only 2 of those error was allowed to be handled before the message was sent to the dead-queue. 
3. Given one specific message where the user code throw an error, I expect ``processError`` to be given the opportunity to complete before any new attempt to process the same message.
4. I expect the message to be automatically completed if in ``peekLock`` mode with ``autoCompleteMessages`` set to true and the ``processMessage`` handler complete without any issue.

**Additional context**

I used the sample for demonstration purposes, I stumbled upon this issue when I noticed that my application would log a storm of message logs where I could see the same message being received multiple times with very few errors being logged despite that every attempt at processing the message failed.

Here's the modified sample.
Set both ``SIMULATE_PROCESSING_ERROR`` and ``MANUAL_AUTOCOMPLETE_MESSAGE`` to true to test the starvation case.

Set both to false to test the case where the message never completes.

